mediaNotes: Male Cerulean Warbler singing in top of deciduous tree along roadside. Equipment Notes: SD 702 HPF on at 80Hz, -12dB per octave.

**This is not an error.  This is a confirmed Cerulean Warbler singing like a Hooded Warbler!  The bird flew down to within 4 meters of me at eye-level.  I put the microphone on him hoping he would call or sing at close range.  It took me a couple of songs to realize it was not a HOWA singing behind the Cerulean, but the Cerulean itself.  It came to within 5 feet of me in a sapling and I observed it singing this song multiple times. 100% confidence in ID despite anomolous song. 
 Retired UNCA professor Charlotte Goedsche has recorded this bird or a similar phenomenon in a different Cerulean near this location in past years.

Contributed for the female bird song project: femalebirdsong.org; female Cerulean Warbler singing from her nest (female song previously undocumented in this species); nest stage is incubation; ID'd and sexed visually, but also sexed based on incubation behavior, which is a female-only behavior in this species; this cut of songs given entirely by the female while she sat on her nest; we documented her singing like this from June 14-22, which largely overlapped with the incubation stage of her nest; will upload video showing the female singing while incubating at a later date
